This paper is about dependency parsing using a neural network approach, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses a bidirectional recurrent neural network, which falls under the category of machine learning (ML), specifically deep learning. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses a distribution over possible heads for each word, which is a probabilistic approach, falling under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), specifically probabilistic reasoning. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions a maximum spanning tree algorithm, which is a graph theory algorithm, falling under the category of neural networks and learning (NE). Therefore, cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is another likely sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions evaluating the approach on images, which suggests the use of computer vision (CV) techniques, falling under the category of computer vision and pattern recognition. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is another likely sub-category.
